TAIL(1)                        User Commands                        TAIL(1)

NAME
    tail - output the last part of a file

SYNOPSIS
    tail [OPTION]... [FILE]...

DESCRIPTION
    Print the last part of each FILE to standard output. With no options,
    the last 10 lines are shown.

    This is the unmodified GNU coreutils tail(1), ported to Horus and run as
    a ring-3 program from /bin/tail over the fs_server.

OPTIONS
    -n [+]N    print the last N lines (or, with '+', from line N onward)
    -c [+]N    print the last N bytes (or, with '+', from byte N onward)
    -q         never print file-name headers
    -v         always print file-name headers

    -f follow (keep printing as the file grows) is best-effort on Horus: it
    polls rather than pacing to a wall clock, because the kernel exposes no
    timed sleep to ring 3. Run `tail --help` for the full option list.

EXIT STATUS
    0 on success, non-zero on error (e.g. a file that cannot be read).

SEE ALSO
    head(1), cat(1), wc(1), hier(7)
